“I am very certain we’re not going to run out of food.”In the food industry, a rapid adjustment to this unprecedented shift in demand is underway.
They might especially wish they weren’t if they knew, say food supply experts, that the lessons they’re getting are likely wrong.
Melanie Stetson Freeman/Staff Food supply chain expert Chris Mejia Argueta, director of the Food and Retail Operations Lab at MIT, poses by his home, on April 7, 2020, in Cambridge, Massachusetts.
Now suppliers are scrambling to redirect food from restaurants and food service to retailers for at-home eating, a sudden and unprecedented shift in consumption.
As a supply-chain scientist, Mr. Mejia-Argueta has looked at what could happen to severely disrupt food production and distribution.